'''Muhamad Aly Rifai''', [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] ([[Arabic]] '''الدكتور محمد علي الرفاعي''') is a distinguished [[Arab American]] [[Internist]] and [[Psychiatrist]] and a renowned clinician researcher who is known for describing the association between psychiatric disorders and [[Hepatitis C]].<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb4345/is_1_31/ai_n28981858/?tag=content;col1/] Psychiatric disorders more likely in HCV patients, Clinical Psychiatry News, January 2003. Accessed August 23, 2009</ref> He co-authored the first clinical report <ref name="PMID 11739908">{{cite journal |author= Yovtcheva, S; Rifai, MA; Moles, JK et al |title=Psychiatric co-morbidities in patients with Hepatitis C |journal=[[Psychosomatics]] |volume=42 |issue=5 |pages=411–415|year=2001 |month=September |pmid=11739908 |doi= 10.1176/appi.psy.42.5.411|url=http://psy.psychiatryonline.org/cgi/content/full/42/5/411}}</ref><ref name="Focus">{{cite journal |author= Yovtcheva, S; Rifai, MA; Moles, JK et al |title=Psychiatric co-morbidities in patients with Hepatitis C |journal=[[Focus (journal)|Focus]] |volume=3 |pages=261–265|year=2005|doi= |url=http://focus.psychiatryonline.org/cgi/content/full/3/2/261 |issue=2}}</ref> detailing the association between Hepatitis C Infection and Psychiatric Disorders.<ref name="Focus Review">{{cite journal |author= Rifai, MA; Rosenstein DL|title=Hepatitis C and Psychiatry |journal=[[Focus (journal)|Focus]] |volume=3 |pages=194–202|year=2005 |doi= |url=http://focus.psychiatryonline.org/cgi/content/full/3/2/194 |issue=2}}</ref><ref name="Psychosomatics SARTP">{{cite journal |author= Rifai MA, Moles JK, Lehman LP, Vander Linden BJ |title=Hepatitis C screening and treatment outcomes in patients with substance use / dependence disorders |journal=[[Psychosomatics]] |volume=47 |pages=112–121|year=2006 |doi=10.1176/appi.psy.47.2.112 |pmid= 16508022 |issue= 2}}</ref><ref name="Psychiatric Services">{{cite journal |author= Rifai MA, Moles JK, Short DD|title=Hepatitis C treatment eligibility and outcomes in patients with psychiatric disorders |journal=[[Psychiatric Services]] |volume=47 |pages=570–572|year=2006 |doi=10.1176/appi.ps.57.4.570 |pmid= 16603757 |issue= 4 }}</ref> He was awarded the [[American Psychiatric Association]] / American Psychiatric Institute for Research and Education Scholarship for research on severe mental illness <ref>[http://www.psychiatricnews.org/pnews/00-05-19/scholarships.html] Rifai Awarded APA/APIRE scholarship for research on severe mental illness and Hepatitis C,  Psychiatric News May 19, 2000, Accessed August 23, 2009</ref>  and [[Hepatitis C]]. Rifai is a fellow of the [[American College of Physicians]], the [[American Psychiatric Association]] and the Academy of Psychosomatic Medicine. He is the recipient of the Academy of Psychosomatic Medicine prestigious William Webb Fellowship.  He is also the recipient of several clinical excellence awards from the [[National Institute of Mental Health]] and the [[American College of Physician Executives]]. He is a clinical professor of [[Medicine]] and [[Psychiatry]] at [[The Commonwealth Medical College]].

==Training and career==
He obtained his [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] with honors from [[Aleppo University]] Faculty of Medicine in 1996 and received a Neuroscience National Research Service Award funded by the [[National Institute of Mental Health]]. Rifai completed a neuroscience research training fellowship at the [[University of Tennessee Health Science Center]], College of Medicine in Memphis (1996–1998). In 1998 he began training in the combined Internal Medicine and Psychiatry program at the [[University of Virginia School of Medicine]], Carilion Health System Program ([[Carilion Clinic]]) in Roanoke and Salem, [[Virginia]]. Dr. Rifai then competed fellowship training in Psychosomatic Medicine and Psychiatric Research at the [[National Institute of Mental Health]] in Bethesda, Maryland (2003–2005). Rifai is certified by the [[American Board of Internal Medicine]] in Internal Medicine and by the [[American Board of Psychiatry and Neurology]] in Psychiatry and Psychosomatic Medicine. Dr. Rifai is board certified in Medical Management by the [[American College of Physician Executives]]. He is the Chairman of the Department of Psychiatry at [http://ghmh.org/content/ Blue Mountain Health System] in [[Lehighton]] and [[Palmerton]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Rifai serves on an advisory panel on [[Hepatitis C]] for the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]]. He presents a yearly educational course to psychiatrists on Hepatitis C during the [[American Psychiatric Association]] annual meeting.

==Research on Hepatitis C and psychiatric illness==
Dr. Rifai demonstrated the first evidence indicating a significant association between Hepatitis C and psychiatric disorders ([[Psychotic]], [[Affective]], [[Anxiety]] and [[Substance abuse|Substance use]]).<ref name="Focus"/><ref>[http://www.psychiatrist.com/pcc/pccpdf/v04n04/v04n0411.pdf] The Prevalence of Psychiatric Disorders in Veterans with Hepatitis C , Journal of Clinical Psychiatry , November 14, 2001. Accessed August 25, 2009</ref> The [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] immediately commissioned a larger study to replicate these findings and confirmed the significant association between Hepatitis C and psychiatric disorders.<ref name="Gastroenterology">{{cite journal |unused_data= PMID 12145801 |author= El-Serag HB, Kunik M, Richardson P, Rabeneck L|title=Psychiatric disorders among veterans with hepatitis C infection |journal=[[Gastroenterology (journal)|Gastroenterology]] |volume=123|issue=2|pages=476–482|year=2002|month= August|doi=10.1053/gast.2002.34750 |pmid=12145801}}</ref> Rifai advocated for screening patients with psychiatric disorders for [[Hepatitis C]].<ref name="Annals of Internal Medicine">{{cite journal |author= Rifai, MA  |title=Hepatitis C patients with psychiatric illness: the forgotten |journal=[[Annals of Internal Medicine]] |volume=141|issue=9|pages=715|year=2004|doi= |url=http://www.annals.org/cgi/eletters/141/9/715#581}}</ref> He spoke to ''[[The New York Times]]'' about the shame associated with the [[Hepatitis C]] diagnosis.<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/12/health/psychology/12case.html?] In a judgmental world she was afraid to get sick by Gretchen Cook, The New York Times, April 12, 2005. Accessed August 25, 2009</ref>

